aVPresident Donald Trump's decision to end the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program is an effort to fix a broken system, former Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore told Newsmax TV.\u000a\u000aDuring an appearance on "Newsmax Now," Gilmore and host Bill Tucker spoke about the future of DACA, which is slated to be phased out in March.\u000a\u000aImportant: Newsmax TV is available on DirecTV Ch. 349, U-Verse 1220, and FiOS 615. If your cable operator does not have Newsmax TV just call and ask them to put us on \u2013 Call toll-free 1-844-500-6397 and we will connect you right away to your cable operator!\u000a\u000aFor more places to Find Newsmax TV \u2013 Click Here Now\u000a\u000a"Well I think what [Trump is] doing is cleaning up an old mess," said Gilmore, a Republican who served from 1998-2002. "The problem is that the so-called Dreamers are here illegally, and you know President Obama didn't do them any favors by keeping their status illegal and just letting them go on and start their lives and do all that kind of thing when he had a deferred deportation program."\u000a\u000aGilmore echoed others by saying it is now up to Congress to write and pass legislation that would serve as a permanent solution to the issue. Roughly 800,000 people have benefitted from DACA, which allows people who illegally came to the United States as children with their parents to stay here under certain conditions.\u000a\u000a"I think we've got to get the law straight, and that, I think, is really what's bothering people, and it's something that we've got to do," Gilmore said. "You can define the Dreamers any way you want to by statute, but you can't just have an illegal situation."
