aVBroadcaster Rush Limbaugh will evacuate South Florida because of the Hurricane Irma, although he said that the media's coverage of the hurricane was designed to boost ratings and advance the climate change agenda.\u000a\u000a"I'm not going to get into details because of the security nature of things, but it turns out that we will not be able to do the program here tomorrow\u2026We'll be on the air next week, folks, from parts unknown," Limbaugh said Thursday on his program, according to ThinkProgress.\u000a\u000a"Tomorrow is going to be problematic," he said. Doing the show Friday would be "legally impossible."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCNN security analyst Juliette Kayyem said in a tweet that it's "legally impossible" because evacuation is mandatory in Limbaugh's Palm Beach County area.\u000a\u000aOmg. "Legally impossible" = mandatory evacuation. This is too rich. Real deniers don't listen to evacuation orders. Fight the power, Rush. https://t.co/0NAqMHxxDG \u2014 Juliette Kayyem (@juliettekayyem) September 8, 2017\u000a\u000aOn his show Tuesday, Limbaugh said, "So there is a desire to advance this climate change agenda, and hurricanes are one of the fastest and best ways to do it. You can accomplish a lot just by creating fear and panic."\u000a\u000aNBC's "Today" weatherman Al Roker and other weather officials rebuked Limbaugh for his Tuesday comments, saying he was risking lives by diminishing the seriousness of the storm.\u000a\u000aRoker also took aim at Limbaugh in a Wednesday tweet.
